HANTAVIRUS PULMONARY SYNDROME UPDATE 2004 - THE AMERICAS (05)
*************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[The CDC web-site
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hanta/hps/index.htm>
identifies hantaviruses in the New World as follows.
North America:
Hantaviruses in the New World are associated with hantavirus pulmonary
syndrome (HPS). Sigmodontine rodents carry the hantaviruses that cause HPS
and are found throughout the Americas. Sin Nombre virus, carried by
_Peromyscus maniculatus_, is the predominant cause of HPS in the United
States and Canada. Mononghela, New York, Bayou, and Black Creek Canal
viruses also cause HPS and are found in eastern Canada and in the eastern
and southeastern United States.
In South and Central America, hantaviruses that have been identified as
causing HPS are Andes virus in Argentina and Chile; Andes-like viruses
including Oran, Lechiguanas, and Hu39694 in Argentina; Laguna Negra virus in
Bolivia and Paraguay; Bermejo virus in Argentina; Juquitiba virus in Brazil;
and Choclo virus in Panama.
Numerous other hantaviruses have been identified but have not been linked to
human disease. - Mod.CP]
In this update:
[1] Brazil: Update on the epidemiological situation
[2] USA: 2 cases HPS, July 2004 - West Virginia
******
[1] Brazil: Update on the epidemiological situation
Date: Fri 8 Oct 2004
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: EID Updates: Emerging and Reemerging Infectious Diseases,
Region of the Americas, Vol. 2, No. 26,6 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://www.paho.org/English/AD/DPC/CD/eid-eer-2004-oct-06.htm>
Epidemiological situation of hantavirus in Brazil
-----------------------------------------------
Up to 5 Sep 2004, 85 new cases of hantavirus infection were confirmed
in Brazil as Hantavirus Cardiopulmonary Syndrome (HPS). The number of
cases reported to date for this year [2004] is equivalent to the
total number of cases reported for 2003 [illustrated in a figure, not
shown here]. These 85 cases were detected in 10 (37 percent) of the
Brazilian states, with only the northeastern region not registering
cases. Nearly 60 percent of the cases were detected in Minas Gerais
and the Federal District. The geographical spread of the disease is
limited to 45 areas or municipalities of transmission, or 0.8 percent
of the total number of Brazilian municipalities [illustrated by a
figure, not shown here].
Cases [were] detected every month during the year [2004], with 56.5
percent (48) reported from May to July and an increase in the number
of cases from April onwards [illustrated by a figure, not shown here].
Concerning the profile of the persons admitted to the hospital for
HPS this year [2004], 69.4 percent (59 cases) were men and 81.2
percent (69) were between 21 and 50 years of age (Tables 1 and 2).
Age ranged from 15 to 71 years, with the mean and median ages 34 and
36, respectively. The mode was 24 years.
Table 1: Hantavirus -- Number and Percentage of Cases by Age Group
(Brazil, 2004*)
Age Group / Cases / Percent / Cumulative percent
<10 years / - / - / -
11-20 years / 12 / 14.1 / 14.1
21-30 years / 23 / 27.1 / 41.2
31-40 years / 16 / 18.8 / 60.0
41-50 years / 18 / 2.2 / 81.2
51-60 years / 12 / 14.1 / 95.3
61-70 years / 3 / 3.5 / 98.8
>70 years / 1 / 1.2 / 100.0
Total / 85 / 100 / [not applicable]
[Source: Sistema de Vigilancia em Saude, Ministerio da Saude (SVS/MS)
(System of Health Surveillance, Ministry of Health, Brazil).]
(*) preliminary data
Nearly 65 percent of the deaths occurred among males; however, case
fatality was 24 percent higher among women (Table 2).
Table 2: Hantavirus - Number of Cases and Deaths and Case-Fatality
Rate by Gender (Brazil, 2004*)
Gender / Cases / Percent / Deaths / Percent / Case-Fatality Rate (Percent)
Male / 59 / 69.4 / 22 / 64.7 / 37.3
Female / 26 / 30.6 / 12 / 35.3 / 46.2
Total / 85 / 100.0 / 34 / 100.0 / 40.0
[Source: Sistema de Vigilancia em Saude, Ministerio da Saude (SVS/MS)
(System of Health Surveillance, Ministry of Health, Brazil).]
(*) preliminary data
Of the 85 cases, 51 of the patients (60 percent) were released from
the hospital. During the period under analysis, the State of Minas
Gerais presented the lowest case-fatality rate of 32 percent among
the 25 cases; followed by Santa Catarina (with 37.5 percent) and the
Federal District (with 38.5 percent). Altogether, these states
reported 69.4 percent of all cases (or 59 of them). The average
case-fatality rate now stands at 40 percent, which is lower than in
the past (Table 3).
Table 3: Hantavirus - Number of Cases and Deaths and Case-Fatality
Rate by State (Brazil, 2004*)
State / Cases / Percent / Deaths / Case-Fatality Rate (Percent)
AM / 2 / 2.4 / - / -
DF / 26 / 30.6 / 10 / 38.5
